{{Main|Maryland Terrapins football under Jim Tatum (1947â1955)}} {{NCAATeamFootballSeason |Year=1947 |Team=Maryland Terrapins |Image= |Conference=Southern Conference |Division= |ShortConference=SoCon |Record= 7â2â2 |ConfRecord= 4â2â1 |CoachRank= |APRank= |HeadCoach=[[Jim Tatum]] |OffCoach= |DefCoach= |Captain= [[George Simler]] |OScheme=[[Split-T]] |DScheme= |StadiumArena=[[Old Byrd Stadium|Byrd Stadium (original)]] |Champion= |BowlTourney=[[1948 Gator Bowl|Gator Bowl]] vs. [[1947 Georgia Bulldogs football team|Georgia]] |BowlTourneyResult=T, 20â20 }} The '''1947 Maryland Terrapins football team''' represented the [[University of Maryland, College Park|University of Maryland]] in [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] (NCAA) [[college football]] in its [[1947 college football season|27th season]] as a member of the [[Southern Conference]].
[[Jim Tatum]] served as the first-year head coach and replaced [[Clark Shaughnessy]] who had been asked to resign. Tatum replaced Shaughnessy's pass-oriented version of the [[T formation]] with the [[option offense|option-heavy]] [[split-T]] offense. [[Maryland Terrapins football under Jim Tatum (1947â1955)|During his nine-year tenure]] at [[College Park, Maryland|College Park]], Tatum would become the [[winning percentage|winningest]] coach in school history. In 1947, he got off to a good start and significantly improved from Shaughnessy's 3â6 record of the season prior.
The highlight of the season was a berth in the [[1948 Gator Bowl]], the first postseason game in school history. NCAA-scoring leader [[Lu Gambino]] ran for 165 yards and scored all three touchdowns for Maryland. The game ultimately ended in a stalemate.
